0.5.0
-- Migrate the AMQP transport from the bundled ~2010 librabbitmq fork to the maintained rabbitmq-c client library (https://github.com/alanxz/rabbitmq-c, 0.8+). This is a C/build change only; the SQL interface and the amqp.broker schema (including the TLS columns) are unchanged.
   -- New build dependency: librabbitmq-dev (Ubuntu/Debian, the primary target), librabbitmq-devel (RHEL/Fedora), or "brew install rabbitmq-c" (macOS). The Makefile locates it via "pkg-config librabbitmq" with a "-lrabbitmq" fallback, and no longer links OpenSSL directly (rabbitmq-c handles TLS internally).
   -- Headers are included compatibly for both the new <rabbitmq-c/...> layout (0.14+) and the top-level <amqp.h> layout shipped by Ubuntu's librabbitmq-dev, selected at compile time with __has_include.
   -- TLS now uses rabbitmq-c's native amqp_ssl_socket_* (TLSv1.2+ minimum, peer + hostname verification, custom CA, mutual TLS), replacing the bundled custom OpenSSL handshake. The ssl/ssl_verify/ssl_cacert/ssl_cert/ssl_key columns are honoured as before.
   -- Connection optimizations from 0.4.5 are preserved (reconnect backoff, SO_KEEPALIVE, TCP_NODELAY, operational socket timeout, cached broker config). Native sockets are opened with amqp_socket_open_noblock() under the connect timeout, then tuned for steady-state I/O.
   -- The "mandatory" / unroutable-return reporting from 0.4.6 is preserved. rabbitmq-c has no return callback, so returns are now surfaced by polling for basic.return frames (before tx commit, and after an autonomous publish made with mandatory=true).
-- High-load / unreliable-broker hardening (the publish path is synchronous and runs inside PostgreSQL backends, so a slow or failing broker must never be able to stall the database tier):
   -- Volatility fix: publish(), autonomous_publish(), exchange_declare() and disconnect() are now VOLATILE (were incorrectly IMMUTABLE). IMMUTABLE let the planner constant-fold a call with all-constant arguments at plan time and reuse the cached boolean, so e.g. a prepared statement or a PL/pgSQL function publishing with literal arguments would publish once and then silently never again. ALTER FUNCTION in the update script preserves grants.
   -- Bounded commit-path I/O: amqp_tx_commit/tx_rollback run inside the COMMIT/ABORT xact callback, after the PostgreSQL transaction is already durable and while heavyweight locks are still held. They are now bounded by a small, separate pg_amqp.commit_timeout_ms (default 2s) instead of the 30s steady-state timeout, and the teardown on failure no longer performs a blocking Connection.Close handshake -- so a slow/half-open broker can no longer freeze every committing backend (and pile up lock waiters / connection-pool slots) for up to 60s.
   -- Phase-split, GUC-tunable timeouts (all milliseconds): pg_amqp.connect_timeout_ms (default 2000), pg_amqp.handshake_timeout_ms (2000, bounds login/channel.open/tx.select per failover host), pg_amqp.operation_timeout_ms (30000, steady-state publish), pg_amqp.commit_timeout_ms (2000), and pg_amqp.connect_budget_ms (default 0 = unlimited) which optionally caps the total wall-clock time spent trying all failover hosts in one connect attempt. The old single 30s timeout governed every phase; the login handshake in particular could block 30s per failover host.
   -- Loud, no-longer-silent message loss: when a channel that errored mid-transaction (or vanished) reaches commit with buffered messages, or when the commit-time tx_commit itself fails, a WARNING now reports the broker_id and the count of messages being lost (these already returned true to the caller and cannot be recovered because PostgreSQL has already committed). Previously the whole buffered batch was discarded with no log line.
   -- Savepoint / subtransaction safety: a new SubXact callback marks the transaction's buffered messages for discard (with a WARNING) when a savepoint or PL/pgSQL EXCEPTION block rolls back, so work that was rolled back no longer emits phantom AMQP messages at top-level commit.
   -- Two-phase commit safety: publishing via amqp.publish() in a transaction that is then PREPAREd now raises an ERROR at PRE_PREPARE (instead of leaving the buffer tied to the wrong transaction's outcome). Use autonomous_publish() or an outbox with 2PC/XA.
   -- exchange_declare() no longer poisons the shared connection's transactional buffer on failure (a failed declare previously set the error flag and silently discarded co-transaction publish() messages at commit).
   -- Broker flow-control awareness: the client now advertises the connection.blocked capability at login and surfaces connection.blocked/unblocked and broker-initiated channel/connection closes by draining frames before every publish; while blocked (broker resource alarm) publishes fail fast instead of stalling on a full socket buffer. The post-publish amqp_get_rpc_reply (which only echoed stale RPC state for an async basic.publish) is no longer consulted.
   -- Faster dead-peer detection: TCP keepalive is tuned (idle 30s / interval 10s / 3 probes where the platform supports it) instead of relying on the ~2h OS default, so a black-holed connection is detected in tens of seconds. Heartbeat stays 0 (a synchronous backend cannot service AMQP heartbeats while idle).
   -- Reconnect-storm mitigation: the fixed 2s reconnect backoff is now exponential (2s base, 30s cap) with per-backend jitter and a per-backend failover start index, so a fleet recovering from a broker outage spreads its reconnects and its connections across cluster nodes instead of synchronizing on one.
   -- Robustness: the amqp.broker failover list is no longer truncated to 100 rows (SPI tcount 0); broker ports are validated to 1..65535; ssl_verify=false now emits a WARNING (the server certificate is not validated); exchange_declare() tolerates NULL boolean arguments; an optional pg_amqp.max_body_bytes guard (default 0 = unlimited) rejects oversized bodies before contacting the broker; and a bounded graceful close runs at backend exit.
   -- Transactional outbox (new amqp.outbox table + amqp.publish_outbox() / amqp.publish_outbox_batch()): for traffic that must not be lost, enqueue with publish_outbox() inside the business transaction (a plain INSERT, atomic with your data, off the broker's commit path) and ship to the broker out of band with publish_outbox_batch() (FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED, so multiple relay workers can run; drive it from pg_cron or a polling worker). Delivery is at-least-once: the relay re-sends on retry and, absent publisher confirms, cannot detect a broker that accepts-then-drops, so consumers should be idempotent.
   -- STILL NOT addressed in-extension (architectural): there is one broker connection (2 channels) per PostgreSQL backend with no pooling, and the inline publish path provides no publisher-confirm delivery guarantee (the outbox decouples and durably stores messages but, lacking confirms, is at-least-once rather than exactly-once).
   -- NOTE: requires validation against a live broker before release. The bundled src/librabbitmq sources are now unused and can be removed once validated.

0.4.6
-- Add an optional "mandatory" parameter (default false) to publish() and autonomous_publish(). When true, the broker returns unroutable messages instead of silently dropping them, and a WARNING is emitted reporting the reply code, exchange and routing key. The existing basic.return plumbing in the bundled librabbitmq is now wired up via amqp_set_basic_return_cb(). For transactional publish the return is surfaced at commit time; on the autonomous (non-transactional) channel detection is best-effort because returns are only read on a subsequent broker operation. Function signatures change, so the update script drops and recreates the two functions (preserving EXECUTE privileges).

0.4.5
-- Connection handling optimizations (C code only, no schema change):
   -- Reconnect backoff: after a failed connect the broker is not retried for a short window (AMQP_RECONNECT_BACKOFF_SEC, default 2s). A statement that publishes many rows while the broker is down now fails fast instead of paying a full connect timeout per row.
   -- TCP keepalive (SO_KEEPALIVE) and TCP_NODELAY are now set on the broker socket so dead peers (broker restart, idle NAT/firewall drop) are detected and small publish frames are not delayed by Nagle.
   -- Split the connect timeout from the operational timeout. The 2s connect timeout no longer doubles as the recv/send timeout for the life of the connection; once connected, a larger operational timeout (AMQP_OP_TIMEOUT_SEC, default 30s) is applied so large messages or a momentarily slow broker do not spuriously time out and reconnect.
   -- Broker configuration (amqp.broker row) is read once via SPI and cached for the connection's lifetime instead of being re-queried on every reconnect. The cache is invalidated by amqp.disconnect(), which is now how configuration changes (rotated credentials, new failover host) take effect without restarting the backend.
   -- As a side effect of the above, failover across multiple hosts no longer leaks the failed amqp_connection_state_t between attempts, and the connection index is preserved across reconnects so failover advances to the next host.

0.4.4
-- Fix OpenSSL compatibility for hostname verification by guarding use of X509_CHECK_FLAG_NO_PARTIAL_WILDCARDS when it is not available in system headers.
-- Fix declaration ordering in TLS read helper to satisfy strict -Wdeclaration-after-statement toolchains.
-- Handle PostgreSQL 18 XactEvent callback enum values (PRE_COMMIT, PARALLEL_PRE_COMMIT, PRE_PREPARE, PARALLEL_COMMIT, PARALLEL_ABORT) to avoid switch warnings on newer server headers.

0.4.3
-- Fix K&R-style function declarations (local_amqp_get_a_bs, local_amqp_get_bs, local_amqp_disconnect) to use ANSI C prototypes. Required for PostgreSQL 16+ which enforces -Werror with strict C11/C17 compilation, and mandatory for PostgreSQL 18 compatibility.
-- Replace deprecated gethostbyname() with getaddrinfo() in the bundled librabbitmq socket layer. This adds IPv6 support, ensures thread-safety, and improves compatibility with modern RabbitMQ deployments on dual-stack or IPv6 hosts.
-- Add TLS/SSL support via OpenSSL. New amqp.broker columns (ssl, ssl_verify, ssl_cacert, ssl_cert, ssl_key) control the TLS configuration per broker. Supports server certificate verification, custom CA bundles, and mutual TLS (client certificates). Requires TLSv1.2 or newer. Makefile now links against -lssl -lcrypto.
-- Rename confusingly-named PG91 Makefile variable to PG_GE91 for clarity.

0.4.2
--  Sets the maximum channels for a connection to that of the server which has been changed from 0 to 2047 in recent version of rabbitmq
0.4.1
-- Clarify commit warning messages with error codes. Also corrected the warning message for rollbacks (Github Pull Request #15).


0.4.0
-- Add support for commonly used amqp message properties (delivery_mode, content_type, reply_to and correlation_id) for publish() and autonomous_publish(). Many thanks to netalien for the contribution. (Github PR #13).
-- This software is now only supported as a PostgreSQL Extension. PG versions prior to 9.1 and means to install it without the extension system are no longer officially supported. PostgreSQL 9.0 is EOL as of Sept 2015 (http://www.postgresql.org/support/versioning/)
-- Added support for upgrading extension installation from 0.3.0 to 0.4.0. If pg_amqp is not installed as an extension, you must turn it into one before updating. See the README for instructions on doing this.
-- Named all SQL function parameters so explicit value setting can be used.


